{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608749/1958040501/0231.xml":{"full_text":"sttenina J&fctf\nWith Sunday Morning fcdition\nPublished by\nTHI EVENING STAR NEWSPAPER COMPANY\nWASHINGTON 4, D. C.\nSamuel H. KauHmann\nPreiMWnt\nBanjamin M. McKalway\nMtor\nMAIN OFFICE: 11th S*. and Panniylvania Ava. (4)\nNEW YORK: 342 Maditon A.\u00ab. (17)\nCHICAGO: 221 N. la Salla St. (1)\nDETROIT: Naw Canttr Building (2)\nSAN FRANCISCO: Run lullding (4)\nIOS ANGELES: 1242 Wan Bth St. (5)\nEUROPEAN BUREAU\u2014\nPARIS, FRANCE: 21 Rua Da larri\nDtiivtred by Carrier\nEuaning and Sunday Sunday Evening\nMonthly 195 Par l\u00bbua.. .20 Monthly 130\nWeakly 43 Weakly 10.\nNight Final and Sunday 2.00 Night Final Only 1.40\nRates by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance\nAnywhere in the United Stater\nEvening and Sunday Sunday Evening\nI yaor 2800 1 year ...12.00 1 y\u00bbar 18 00\n4 month* ....14 30 4 months... 4.30 4 months 4.23\n3 months 7.30 1 months 3.30 3 months 473\n1 month 2.40 1 month 1.30 1 month 200\nTelephone: Sterling 3 3000\nEntered at the Pott Office, Washington, D. C.\nas second class mall matter\nMember of the Associated Press\nThe Associated Press it entitled exclusively to the use for\nrepublicotion of all the local news printed in this newspaper\nos well as A. P. newt dispatches.\nSATURDAY. APRIL 5. 1958\nA-4\nFCC Ethics\nIt is very doubtful that the enforced\nadoption of a \u201ccode of ethics\u201d will prove\nto be a satisfactory solution to the prob\nlems that have emerged from the Inves\ntigation of the Federal Communications\nCommission.\nThe problems, or the things that\nare wrong, are obvious. It is wrong, we\nthink, for a member of the FCC to ac\ncept money for making a speech at a\nmeeting of the industry he is supposed\nto help regulate. It is wrong for a\nmember to collect per diem allowances\nfrom the Government when the indus\ntry is paying his expenses. And it is\nalso wrong, we believe, for FCC mem\nbers to accept color television sets or\nanything else of comparable value from\nthe industry.\nThe question is not whether these\npractices are legal or illegal. They may\nbe entirely Vlthin the law. But it is an\nunwholesome thing for members of any\nregulatory agency to accept favors from\nthe industry it is supposed to regulate.\nIf acceptance of favors does not corrupt,\nit at least may tend to corrupt. And,\nonce exposed, the practice is bound to\nImpair public confidence in the agency.\nAn imposed code of ethics is hardly\nthe answer. A man is either sensitive\nor insensitive to the distinction between\nwhat is proper and what isn\u2019t. If he\ndoesn\u2019t know the'difference he should\nnot be serving on the FCC or on any\nsimilar agency. The real remedy is to\nchoose men for these jobs who do know\nthe difference.\n'Brains 1 Dinner\nA unique adaptation of the tradi\ntional \u201cold school spirit\u201d brand of stu\ndent \u201cpep\u201d rally, usually featuring scho\nlastic sports heroes, will make its debut\nApril 21 at the George Mason Junior-\nSenior High School in Falls Church. But\nthe students to be honored on this occa\nsion will not be those who have distin\nguished themselves on the gridiron, the\ndiamond or the cinder track. They will\nbe students who have been standouts in\nthe field of learning. The idea of giving\na banquet for academic champions is a\nnovel one, according to the National\nEducation Association, but the George\nMason High example ought to be widely\nfollowed in order to stimulate interest\nin scholarship.\nThe plan for such a banquet origi\nnated with Principal Raymond R. Reed.\nHe had noted that George Mason\u2019s nu\nmerous athletic stars were honored reg\nularly at rallies and banquets, as was\nproper. But the school also has a splen\ndid record in turning out academic stars\n\u2014students who have won scholarships\nand other honors for excellence in their\nstudies. Why not give them recognition,\ntoo, at a banquet in their honor? The\nidea caught on quickly among teachers\nand parents, concerned as they are over\nlagging interest in advanced education.\nThe plan appealed, too, to Dr. James R.\nKillian, jr., scientific adviser to Presi\ndent Eisenhower, and he readily ac\ncepted an invitation to address the ban\nquet. The idea is so worth-while, in fact,\nthat it would not be surprising if it\nspread across the country. We hope so,\nanyway.\nSmashing the Splinters\nOn Monday the Canadian people\ndisposed of two lesser but still signifi\ncant forces in their political framework.\nThe Social Credit Party was left with no\nfederal seats, the Co-operative Com\nmonwealth Federation (CCF) with only\na handful. In the previous Parliament,\neach of these parties had held about two\ndozen seats\u2014virtually all of them from\nWestern Canada.\nThe disappearance of the Social\nCreditors from federal politics will make\nlittle difference to Canadian parlia\nmentary life. This group was founded\nIn the early part of the 1930 s by would\nbe monetary reformers, and has func\ntioned as an ultraconservative move\nment. However, Social Credit provincial\ngovernments still hold sway in far-West\nAlberta and British Columbia. These\nprovinces may be used as a base for the\n\u201cBocreds\u201d to reshape their forces for the\nnext federal election, perhaps four to\nfive years from now.\nThe losses incurred by the CCF will\ncause more general alarm. Although\nvery few Canadians would care to see\nthe CCF form a national government,\nthere is general admiration for the lead\ners of this party, which can very aptly\nbe compared with the American Pro\ngressive movement as it was in the days\nof the La Follettes. M. J. Coldwell, the\nCCF leader, and Btanley Knowles, his\ndeputy, both lost their seats in Parlia\nment. Though represented a very\nmoderate kind of socialism, Canadians\nof all political views admired these men\nfor their mildness of character and\npower of intellect. In Mr. Knowles, the\nHouse of Commons has lost its most\nable parliamentarian.\nPart of the reason for the poor show\ning of these two minor parties may be\nthat Canadian voters were overanxious\nto give Prime Minster Dlefenbaker a\nrenewed mandate, this time in control\nof a clear majority of the Commons\nseats. Again, the election campaign was\nso much a clash of two personalities\u2014\nMr. Dlefenbaker and his Liberal coun\nterpart, Lester Pearson\u2014that Canadians\nmay not have had time to pay attention\nto anyone else. In any case, two small\nbut important groups on the Canadian\npolitical scene have been dealt a body\nblow.\nNew Look at Nasser\nChairman Green of the Senate For\neign Relations Committee has offered\nsome realistic comment, including both\ncriticisms and suggestions, on American\npolicy in the Middle East.\nIn brief, the Rhode Island Senator\ncharges that we really have no policy\nat all toward this vital and troubled\narea, but \u201conly a random assortment\nof hopes, most of them pious, some of\nthem contradictory.\u201d As far as it goes,\nhe acknowledges, the Eisenhower Doc\ntrine has been effective. It has, possibly,\ndeterred overt Communist aggression\nand it has been employed in specific\nnonmilitary crises such as extending\ncritically needed economic support to\nJordan. But it has not impeded the\nCommunist economic and political of\nfensive in the Middle East, and has not\nbeen supplemented\u2014as expected when\napproved by the Senate as an \u201cemer\ngency stopgap\u201d\u2014by a definitive, long\nterm policy toward the region.\nThe Senator's complaint, in effect,\nis that our own Government has not\nrecognized or adjusted itself to the fact\nthat the Middle East, like most of Africa\nand Asia, is undergoing a revolution.\nIn the Middle East, it is a revolution\nbased upon the \u201cdream of Arab unity\u201d\u2014\na dream which may be scoffed at by\nmany, but which gains substance from\nthe merger movements represented in\nthe United Arab Republic and the Arab\nFederation. Our first failure, in the\nlight of these developments, was in\nnot making up our minds whether we\nwanted to \u201cget along\u201d with Colonel\nNasser\u2014an uncertainty reflected in our\non-and-off offer of help on the Aswan\nDam project, our intervention to stop\nthe Suez invasion and our freezing of\nEgyptian assets in this country.\nMr. Green believes we should try to\nget along with Colonel Nasser\u2014even if\nwe do not like his \u201cbrand of imperial\nism\u201d\u2014because it is important that the\nUAR should become \u201ca viable state, both\ndesirous and capable of withstanding\nSoviet penetration.\u201d To do so, it needs\nhelp. If our help is withheld, by a head\nln-the-sand policy of hoping that Colo\nnel Nasser will simply \u201cgo away,\u201d the\nalternative will be Soviet help.\nSenator Green admits that he may\nbe \u201cguilty of generalizing.\u201d He probably\nis aware, too, that any suggestion of\ntrying to \u201cget along\u201d with Colonel Nas\nser is sure to arouse criticism\u2014for vari\nous reasons. But Colonel Nasser and the\nportion of Arab nationalism which he\nrepresents are realities, not myths, and\nthey in turn have great meaning to\nmuch of the Middle East and even to\nsome of the other uncommitted parts of\nAfrica and Asia. The Senator is plead\ning for some positive thinking and posi\ntive action.\na\nUnforeseen Tax Dilemma\nThie Federal Government\u2019s decision\nto speed up construction of the inter\nstate highway system has caught Vir\nginia and some other States unprepared\nfor the change in plans. Current and\nproposed road-building budg|ts have\nbeen geared to the original Federal-aid\nprogram, which wfis scheduled to move\nat a slower pace. Now comes the pros\npect of substantially larger allocations\nto the States from Federal funds, for the\npurpose of combating the recession. The\nStates thus face the dilemma of putting\nup their 10 per cent share of the high\nway speed-up program years ahead of\nschedule or losing the 90 per cent Fed\neral contribution by default. The fiscal\nproblem presented is a serious one for\nmany of the States.\nTake Virginia, for example. The\nState Highway Department, by revising\nroad allotments at the expense of sec\nondary and primary roads not in the\nFederal interstate system, had managed\nto earmark enough money to meet Vir\nginia\u2019s part of the 90 per cent-10 per\ncent bargain. Governor Almond had\npromised that there would be no new\ntaxes proposed, barring unforeseen cir\ncumstances, and the recent General\nAssembly adjourned without raising any\ntax rates. However, an unforeseen cir\ncumstance has come in the form of\ncongressional approval of an antireces\nsion acceleration of the highway pro\ngram. Highway Commissioner Davis has\nwarned that Virginia will not be able to\nput up its enlarged share of Interstate\nhighway funds for fiscal 1959-60 without\nusing up most of the money Intended\nfor secondary and primary roads not in\nthe new system.\nBecause of this outlook, former Gov\nernor Stanley and State Senator Armi\nstead Boothe of Alexandria have pro\nposed a one-cent Increase in the State\ngasoline tax\u2014a measure which Mr. Stan\nley vainly advocated while Governor.\nSince the Legislature will not meet again\nin regular session for two years, Senator\nBoothe has urged Governor Almond to\ncall a special session to deal solely with\nthe highway fund crisis. Any move to\nIncrease the tax on gasoline would be\nunpopular, of course, but the alterna\ntives would be a borrowing program\u2014\nwhich Virginia has tabooed in the past\n\u2014or the loss of the opportunity to receive\nin extra Federal atd^\nThe Easter Bunny Came Early\nLETTERS TO THE STAR\nForeign Trade 'Myths'\nMuch nonsense is being\nwritten and published con\ncerning foreign trade and\ntariffs. One of the popular\nmyths is that other countries\n\u201cdump\u201d commodities on our\nshores and because of their\nlow price undersell the home\narticle. In a free economy\nwe are supposed to have the\nfreedom to buy and sell, yet\nthe very people who are con\nstantly harping about the\n\u201cfree enterprise system\u201d de\nscend on Washington in\nhordes to lobby for a 50 per\ncent duty on everything from\nJapanese needles to Scotch\ntweeds. If there were no de\nmand for certain commodi\nties. they would not be im\nported. No individual or\ngroup of individuals has the\nright to dictate to another\nindividual or group what\nthey should eat. drink, wear\nor ride in. and the attempt to\nrestrict that right of choice\nis arbitrary and unjust. The\nold platitude that the United\nStates cannot compete with\nthe low-paid labor of other\ncountries will not hold water.\nA country where low wages\nare paid is not always the\ncountry which produces at\nthe lowest cost and where\nlabor is most efficient. If\nthe United States, a high\nwage country, wants a high\ntariff to protect its labor,\nwhy is it that protectionists\nin England and Germany,\nwhose workers are paid pro\nportionately less than ours,\nagitate for tariffs to \u201cpro\ntect\" their workers from\nAmerican imports?\nAfter the Napoleonic wars.\nEngland tried to return to\nthe old protective system and\nraised its duties on the im\nportation of foodstuffs. It\nwas only after the near\nrevolt of the factory workers\nin the great mill centers and\nthe vision and statemanship\nof Sir Robert Peel that the\n\"corn laws\" were repealed\nand England entered a great\nera of trade with every coun\ntry of the globe, which\nbrought her great prosperity\nand renown. It was not ab\nsolute free trade, but it was\nthe freest it had been in cen\nturies and much more liberal\nthan the present English\ntrade policy. Queen Victoria\nmay have been prim and\nproper, but she believed in\nher subjects making an\nhonest pound.\nGeorge Maravelas.\nFan Mail\nWhat a blessed relief in\nthese days of recession. Sput\nniks. Soviet propaganda.\nReuther\u2019s oratory. Cuban re\nvolts and all that the flesh\nof man is heir to. to read\nagain Mary McOrory's spar\nkling contributions! Thanks\na thousand times for what\nshe is doing for our hearts\nand minds.\nM. Edmund Speare, Ph.D.\nDefends Reuther\nPerhaps the recent Senate\nRacketeering Committee\u2019s in\nvestigating has proved most\nIlluminating, not as an in\nvestigation of labor unions,\nbut of some of the Republican\nmembers of the committee.\nWhatever other complication\nand confusion you might in\nsert into the investigation,\none two-part fact stands out\ncrystal clear:\n11 1 The Republican mem\nbers can tolerate and even\nadmire a labor leader who is\ncorruptible.\n<2 l They resent and pas\nsionately detest a labor letter\nwho is incorruptible.\nThey badgered Mr. Reuther\nfrom all angles, and when\nthey could not turn up a\nshred of guilt, their tempers\nrose to a pitch of despair, and\nthey picked at his personality,\nspecifically his seemingly im\npregnable morality. They were\nextremely unhappy that all\nwas well. The affair had no\nsimilarity to an investiga\ntion to uncover facts: it was\nrather a desperate attempt\nto destroy a man and a move\nment, by any means.\nAs a small-business man. 1\nhave no interest, econom\nically, in the capital-labor\ncontest except as it might\naffect the Nation as a whole.\nMy interest in this case is a\nhuman interest in its Justice.\nEx-l^braskaa.\nPen names man be used if\nletters carry writers' correct\nnames and addresses. All\nletters are subject to conden\nsation.\n'Pampered' Engineers\nThe Civil Service Commis\nsion, in continuing to pamper\nthe varied engineers in the\nGovernment service by justi\nfying their recent pay in\ncrease and proclaiming their\nrights to a full share of the\nforthcoming Federal pay raise\nby constantly mentioning the\ndifficulty in trying to retain\ncompetent personnel in tiie.se\n\"shortage-category\u201d jobs, has\ndeeply hurt the morale of\nnon-professional career white\ncollar employes. Why is a\nspecific privileged class\nchosen to eat high up on the\nhog in these high cost of liv\ning days? And why is it com\npelling for the Government\nto try and keep the many\nhand-book\u201d variety engi\nneers that clutter its roster?\nThe solution to it all would\nbe to give them the same\nwritten test as the new en\ngineei -applicant would lake\nand. if a passing grade is at\ntained. give them the forth\ncoming pay ra'se a.-> well de\nserved. Is it customary for\nCSC to throw rood money\nafter bad?\nFedrralite.\naa a\nIt Is disconcerting to be\nreminded by Joseph Young\nin \"The Federal Spotlight\"\nof March 27 and backed up\nby Milton Lunch of the\nNational Society of Pro\nfessional Engineres in his\nletter to the editor of\nMarch 31, that our engi\nneers and scientists should\nreceive the full proposed\nFederal pay raise plus\nthe top -of the grade in\ncreases granted by the Civil\nService Commission.\nThe previous progress\nmade by the Civil Serv\nice Commission for career\nemployes has gone backward\nInstead of forward with its\npreferential treatment to en\ngineers and scientists. The\nterm scientist is used rather\nloosely\u2014it should refer in\nstead to chemists and phys\nicists. because not all scien\ntists receive the top-of-grade\nincreases. I work in a Fed\neral department where all of\nthe employes are research\nscientists, yet two of the\nscientists do not receive the\ntop-of-grade increases even\nthough they contribute as\nmuch or more to the same\nline project as the preferred\nscientists. I have seen no\nmore chemists or physicists\nleave the Government in tne\nlast year than any other\nyear. If the engineers and\nscientists were not so gra\nciously granted the top-of\ngrade increases in pay, I\nknow of not one in our group\nwho would leave, except for\nthe scientists who have been\nmorally discriminated against\nfor working just as hard,\njust as long and contribut\ning just as much.\nThe Civil Service Commis\nsion, the National Society of\nProfessional Engineers or any\nother professional society will\nhave to dig long and deep\nfor any kind of legitimate\ntestimony to prove that en\ngineers and scientists de\nserve a salary over at.d above\nthat of other equally quali\nfied employes.\nScientist.\nHighway Bill\nNews of the passage of the\n\"highway bill,\u201d Including the\nbillboard control provision,\nhas Just come from Capitol\nHill, and I hasten to express,\non behalf of the National\nRoadside Committee and all\nof its collaborators, our deep\nappreciation of the fine con-*\ntribution of The Star to this\nsuccess. Your timely and\neffective editorials, and the\nInspired drawing pen of Gib\nCrockett, were a vital con\ntribution to the final decision\nand to education of members\nof Congress.\nWith this hurdle over, we\nmust now turn to the task\nof carrying into effect the\nreasonably mild provisions of\nthe act, at the State level\nMrs. Vance Hood.\nChairman. National Roadside\nCommittee.\nRecession 'Cure-Alls'\nThe divergence of opinion\namong our professional econ\nomists, as regards the \u201ccure\u201d\nfor the current recession, is\nnothing short of astounding.\nI\u2019ve read arguments for in\ncreased public works, argu\nments for more aggressive\nFederal Reserve action, argu\nments for tax cuts and argu\nments for doing nothing at\nall.\nIs it being naive ta rec\nognize all \"cure-alls\u201d must\nultimately be boiled down to\nthe basic premise that all\neconomic activity revolves\naround the balance struck\nbetween incentive and risk?\nIndividuals do not spend\ntheir disposable income on\ngoods whose prices may come\ndown. Corporations do not\nraise production schedules\nand inventory requirements\non any other assumption\nthan existing demand repre\nsents a market potential for\nmaking money.\nCouple this axiom with\nsome other economic facts\nof life. No one type of Fed\neral intervention affects all\nbusiness and all individuals\nin the same manner. There\nis no chance of maintaining\na homogeneous relationship\nbetween purchasing power\nand the particular types of\nproduction no matter what\ntype of economy you em\nbrace. There will always be\na scarcity of some products\nand an oversupply of others.\nDoesn\u2019t it. therefore, be\nhoove our economists and\nlegislators to seek an eco\nnomic climate which places\na premium on business \u2018as\nwell as individuals) working\nout their own economic sal\nvation\u2014through their own\nrecognition of the right kind\nof incentives?\nThis would seem to me to\nbe in the area of tax revision\nbut the right type of revi\nsions.\nDoesn't it seem reasonable\nfor the legislators to provide\nthe tax incentive for business\nto seek its own panacea for re\nnewed prosperity? If the in\ncentive (the opportunity for\nmore profit after taxes) out\nweighs the risks (the like\nlihood of decreased demand\nand spending* our Federal\nGovernment will find less\nneed for having to play the\nrole of Big Brother.\nJohn O. Painter.\nAlerts Homeowners\nLet homeowners be on\nguard against itinerant re\npairmen roaming the city\nand suburbs soliciting roof\nrepairs under the guise and\nthreat that if their recom\nmendations are not followed\nImmediately severe damage\nto life and property may re\nsult.\nWe had an example of the\nalarmism these Pied Pipers\ncreate when the newspapers\nreported a few days ago of\nthe bilking of several hun\ndreds of dollars from an eld\nerly woman. These nomads\nhave been coursing the\nstreets from door to door for\nyears, but currently they we\nfar more numerous and\nruthless than formerly. Their\npitch follows the old pattern:\nthere is loose slate, or in\nsecure gutters or downspouts,\nor chimney bricks in danger\nof falling on somebody's\nhead: the matter cannot wait\nuntil tomorrow; but must be\nremedied today and now.\nThese fellows operate from\nan unlettered truck or from a\ncar. with a ladder tied on top:\nthey have no business ad\ndress. they pay no business\ntaxes, they give receipts on\ndemand only on scraps of\nblank paper and disappear\ninto thin air after they do as\nlittle work as possible and\nget as much for it as they\ncan scare out of their vic\ntims. Solid citizens who\nsmirk at the gullibility of\ntheir brethren who fall for\nthe old pocketbook gimmick\nprove themselves to be blood\nbrothers when they subscribe\nto the machinations of these\nrover boys who are on the\nprowl every working day.\nWhy don't we tighten oui\nlaws on soliciting to require\nthat these gypsies pay a\nfixed fee and establish a\nstable address?\nJohn Q.\nTHE POLITICAL MILL\nBy GOULD LINCOLN\nLawmakers to Feel Home Pulse\nWhen members of Con\ngress return to Washington\nApril 14 after a ten-day\nEaster recess, they will have\nhad an opportunity to learn\nfirst tuuid what their constit\nuents feel and say about the\nrecession, unemployment and\nthe proposed remedies\u2014big\nFederal spending and a ta*\ncut. They will return to take\naction on President Elsen\nhower\u2019s veto of the rigid and\nhigh price supports farm bill\nand to tackle the President's\nprogram of drastic revision\nof the defense setup. And\npresumably they will be in\nbetter position to know what\nshould be done about further\nmeasures to combat the\neconomic recession and spui\nrecovery. They will have be\nfore them, in a short period\na look at the tax returns and\nthe estimates of Government\nrevenue,-and they will have\nadditional figures on unem\nployment and possible pick\nups in the number of Jobs\nfilled.\nUndoubtedly the recess will\nprove valuable, and give\nmembers of Congress an\nopportunity to revise or to\nstrengthen their viewpoints\nof the problems which have\nconfronted them. What the\ncountry actually feels and\ndesires is not always reflected\nin Washington attitudes and\nopinions.\nRecovery Versus Politics\nWhat the country wants is\na halt in the recession and an\neconomic recovery. Whatever\nparty leaders may hope for\npolitical gain growing out\nof recession and unemploy\nment, the people, who are the\nvoters, are more interested in\nrecovery, in getting more jobs.\nThis, however, will not pre\nvent some of the Democratic\nleaders from continuing to\npicture the country as going\nrapidly to the dogs, in their\neffort to make the Eisen\nhower administration and the\nRepublican Party generally\nappear inefficient and un\nmindful of the welfare of the\n\"common man.\u201d They have\nseized upon the recession as\ntheir major issue in*the com\ning congressional and State\nelections and they will work\nit right up to election day\nin November. It's politically\nnatural they should do so.\nUndoubtedly, if the Demo\ncrats held control of the\nWhite House and executive\nbranch of Government, the\nRepublicans would be making\nthe same kind of issues out\nof the recession. The unfor\ntunate part, however, is that,\nfor the sake of political gain,\nthe people should be made to\nlose confidence not only in\nthe Government but in them\nselves.\nWhat some of the Demo\ncratic leaders hope is that\nduring the recess they will\nbe able to gain votes in both\nHouse and Senate for over\nriding the President's veto\nof the farm bill. They will\ncontend that the present re\nTHIS AND THAT\nBy CHARLES f. TRACEWELL\n\"MASSACHUSETTS AVE.\n\u201cDear Sir:\n\"I see where sometimes you\npraise the cat, and I am in\nclined to agree with you, with\none exception.\n\u201cWhy is it these pretty\nand interesting little animals\nbuild up such feuds amongst\nthemselves?\n\u201cI once had 10 of them,\nand no one of them seemed\nto like the others, with the\nresult that there was a con\nstant squabble going on.\n\"I tried separating them,\nkeeping one in one room, and\nothers, the more peaceful, in\nanother, but this didn\u2019t work,\nbecause the belligerent one\nwould get loose and make an\nassault on the others.\n\"I found that one certain\ncat would even fight his own\nbrother on sight\n\u201cHow can you explain this\nin an animal that deserves\npraise in a general way?\n\"Yours truly, A. D. M.\u201d\n\nThe cat is no exception to\nthe traits of all living things.\nIt shows affection in a\nsense\u2014and it shows hate.\nThis hate complex is of the\nessence, evidently, of living\ncreatures.\nToday, unfortunately, this\nthing of hate has growrn to\nteiftlfic proportions.\nWe now witness it bloom\ning, literally, in all the na\ntions of the earth, as an ex\naggerated nationalism grows\nred In the face and demands\nits place in the sun.\n\nThe members of the cat\ntribes, one of the greatest\namong the mammals, are no\nexception.\nHate, spleen, anger, choler\n\u2014call it what one will\u2014\nseems necessary, in such a\nworld as this.\nEven the mildest indi\nvidual. in certain situations,\nfinds a need for some bit of\npure and essential hating in\nhis life.\nIt may not be Christian,\nbut who ever called a cat\nChristian?\nA pure animal, it must re\nspond as nature has taught\nit to respond.\nAt times, the creatures\nseem to be directly ordered in\ntheir movements by a higher\npower, or at least something\noutside and beyond them.\nTake a sick cat.\nIts taste for food is cut off\nas immediately as if it had\nreceived orders not to eat.\nThe animal refuses to look\nat the best food, even when\nit is put before him.\nIf the owner insists on try\ning to force-feed it, as this is\ncession grew out of the farm\nsituation and that the only\nway to cure it is to assure\nthe farmers higher prices\nthrough the operation of high,\nrigid price supports. Neither\ntheir premise nor their pro\nposed cure are necessarily\ncorrect. What happened, for\nexample, in the automobile\nindustry, in the steel indus\ntry, in the tremendous ex\ntension of consumer credits,\nin the boosting of prices and\nthe Increase in costs, includ\ning labor, may have had far\nmore to do with the recession\nthan what happened on the\nfarms. Also, the proposed\ncure of rigid and high price\nsupports is no sure cure. It\nwas in operation little more\nthan a year ago\u2014and it did\nnot bring a halt to declining\nfarm prices and farm income.\nWhat it did do was to con\ntinue the upbuilding of big\nfarm surpluses, with Govern\nment owning billions of dol\nlars worth of farm products\u2014\nin storage.\nHalf-Way Point\nThe Easter recess usually\nmarks half-way in the con\ngressional session. If Con\ngress is to adjourn the last of\nJuly\u2014the date for which con\ngressional leaders shoot\u2014it\nwill have to act, or should act,\nwith promptness on many im\nportant not the\nleast of which is the Presi\ndent's program for increas\ning the effectiveness of our\nnational defense through\nstrengthening and unifying\nthe setup. Not too long ago,\nw hen the Russians had their\nSputniks circling the earth\nand loud cries that we had\nbecome a second-rate power\nwere going up, especially here\nin Washington, there were\ndemands that something be\ndone to unify our defense\neffort. The President prom\nised then to do something\nabout it. He has produced a\nprogram that puts tremendous\npower in the hands of the\nSecretary of Defense as the\nunifying officer. It is a well\nworked-out program. Im\nmediately. however, threats\nof opposition have arisen on\nCapitol Hill.\nIt is to be devoutly hoped\nthat the problem of national\ndefense will not be turned\ninto a political issue and\nkicked around all over the lot.\nThis atomic age leaves no\ntime for such antics. True, a\nfew months ago some of the\nmore ill-advised Democrats\nwere planning to make na\ntional defense their main\ncampaign issue. The Russians,\nthey said, had been permitted\nto get 10 years ahead of us\nin scientific progress with\ntheir missiles and earth satel\nlites. The effort of the Demo\ncrats then was to scare the\nAmerican people into the\nbelief that national defense\nneeded a Democratic admin\nistration in Washington. The\nspeciousness of those argu\nments has now been shown\nup.\ncalled, the creature clenches\nIts teeth and holds Its jaws\nclosed against all intrusion.\nEven it fine beef broth is\nfed it in a medicine dropper,\nthe cat refuses to take more\nthan qpe dropperful.\nBut see what happens\nwhen it begins to get well!\nThen, and usually sud\ndenly. just as if it had re\nceived orders to eat again, it\nshows interest in food, and\nmuch to the pleasure of the\nowner, actually takes a few\nbites of a favorite snack.\n\nThe feuds among these in\nteresting animals cannot be\nexplained on human lines\nexactly.\nThe only thing we can say\nis that they also hate, which\nplays such a part among all\nliving things.\nThis pure animal anger\nwells up. and outsiders can\nsee no reason for it at all.\nThe animals concerned might\nhave an entirely different\nconception.\nIt might be caused by\nnothing more than smell.\nOne cat would not like the\nscent of another, and that\nwould be that. Smells, among\nthese creatures, are all\nimportant. Among human\nbeings, some are very sensi\ntive to disagreeable smells.\nHow much more important,\nthen, is an odor among the\ntrue creatures of this earth,\namong which a certain scent\nmay suddenly be a warning\nof attack and possible death?\nSo flghtin' and feudin' may\nbe considered a part of cat\nlife, when more than two get\ntogether, just as It is among\npeople, only we conceal It\nbetter.\nThe point is. Mrs. Alice M..\nnever keep more than a pair\nof cats at a time, and if you\ngo even as high as four speci\nmens. watch out! If you do,\nyou will have to pay the\npenalty.\nQuestions and Answers\nBy THE HASKIN SERVICE\nQ. Can an Easter lily bought\nas a potted plant be trans\nplanted to the garden?\u2014E. I.\nA. Yes. After it has finished\nblossoming, probably about\nthe middle of April or a bit\nlater. It can be set out in the\ngarden, with about a four to\nsix inch cover of soil over the\nbulb. It may bloom again in\nthe fall: If not, it can be left\nin the ground and, at least\nin milder climates, will come\nup next year to bloom again\nby Easter time.","height":"28881","width":"18321"}}
